<h1 class="hero-h">Healthcare AI playbook <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">for private practices and clinics.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Healthcare AI is uniquely difficult, HIPAA, compounding regulation, physician skepticism, vendor noise, and uniquely high-leverage when done right. This is the practical 2026 playbook for private practices, ambulatory groups, and mid-sized health organizations actually rolling out AI today.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Before anything</span><h2 class="h2">Get the compliance layer right</h2><p class="body">Step zero is not picking a tool. It's confirming your AI usage path is BAA-covered for any workflow touching PHI. Without this, every other decision compounds risk.</p><ul class="ul"><li>Identify which AI platforms your organization has, or can get, a signed BAA with. Claude Enterprise, ChatGPT Enterprise, Microsoft Copilot on M365 with HIPAA configuration are the common paths.</li><li>Map workflows to data classes: which touch PHI (must be BAA-covered), which touch internal-confidential, which touch fully de-identified or public.</li><li>Get sign-off from your compliance officer in writing on the deployment path. One paragraph is enough; it just needs to exist.</li></ul><div class="callout"><p>The most expensive mistake we see in healthcare AI rollouts: clinicians experimenting with free-tier AI tools on patient information "just to see what it can do." Once it happens, you have a breach to disclose. Get the right tier provisioned first; remove the temptation.</p></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Where the leverage actually is</span><h2 class="h2">Five workflows with real ROI</h2><h3 class="h3">1. Patient communications &amp; correspondence</h3><p class="body">Referral letters, lab result explanations, prior-auth letters, post-visit summaries. Cuts physician documentation time 40-60% with a well-built Project. Highest single ROI workflow we see in practice rollouts.</p><h3 class="h3">2. Patient portal triage</h3><p class="body">Categorize incoming portal messages (clinical-urgent, clinical-routine, billing, refill) and draft initial responses. Reduces MA triage time 60-80%; reduces inbox-related physician burnout.</p><h3 class="h3">3. Visit note structuring</h3><p class="body">Convert dictated notes into structured documentation matching your EHR template. Physicians dictate; AI structures. Frees evening charting time.</p><h3 class="h3">4. Prior authorization workflows</h3><p class="body">Drafting prior-auth narratives from clinical context. Significant time recovery; insurance authorizations are universally hated work.</p><h3 class="h3">5. Internal operations</h3><p class="body">Scheduling letters, employee comms, policy updates, vendor correspondence. Non-PHI work that nonetheless eats admin time.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Where to be cautious</span><h2 class="h2">Workflows where AI is not ready</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Clinical decision support</strong>, interesting research, not yet appropriate for production at most practices. Liability exposure outpaces benefit.</li><li><strong>Direct-to-patient chatbots</strong>, quality bar is much higher; one bad answer to a clinical question is a catastrophic outcome.</li><li><strong>Automated coding/billing decisions</strong>, fraud and abuse exposure if AI codes without human review. Use AI to draft; require human sign-off.</li><li><strong>Imaging interpretation</strong>, specialized; use FDA-cleared tools designed for the purpose, not general LLMs.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Team &amp; budget</span><h2 class="h2">What practice rollouts look like</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Practice size</th><th>Year 1 AI spend</th><th>Recommended approach</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Solo / 2-physician</td><td>\$3K-\$12K</td><td>Personal Claude/ChatGPT Enterprise with BAA. One workflow at a time.</td></tr><tr><td>3-8 physicians</td><td>\$8K-\$30K</td><td>Practice-level Claude Enterprise. 2-3 workflows. Light external implementation help.</td></tr><tr><td>8-20 physicians</td><td>\$20K-\$80K</td><td>Multi-function rollout. Dedicated AI lead (physician champion or practice manager). Structured implementation.</td></tr><tr><td>20-100 physicians</td><td>\$60K-\$250K</td><td>Cross-site rollout. Dedicated AI/IT resource. External implementation partner. Integration with EHR considered.</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Physician adoption</span><h2 class="h2">What works, what does not</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Works:</strong> One physician champion who uses the tools and shows colleagues. Group education sessions led by the champion.</li><li><strong>Works:</strong> Letting physicians see the time-savings on their own work before mandating use. Convert with data, not directives.</li><li><strong>Does not work:</strong> Top-down adoption mandates. Physicians resist.</li><li><strong>Does not work:</strong> Generic AI training. Specific workflow training does work.</li><li><strong>Does not work:</strong> AI rollout led by IT without clinical co-leadership.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">ROI markers</span><h2 class="h2">What to measure</h2><ol class="ol"><li>Hours of physician evening charting recovered (most important; biggest burnout driver).</li><li>Inbox response time on patient portal messages.</li><li>Referral letter turnaround time.</li><li>Prior authorization submission time.</li><li>Physician burnout / satisfaction metrics over 6-12 months.</li></ol></div></section>

